{{Wiktionary|Flora}} [[File:Flora Farnese (Napoli).jpg|thumb|Flora Farnese (Napoli)]] {{Ancient Roman religion}}
In [[Roman mythology]], '''Flora''' ({{lang-la|Flōra}}) is a [[Sabine]]-derived [[goddess]] of flowers<ref>H. Nettleship ed., ''A Dictionary of Classical Antiquities'' (1891) p. 238</ref> and of the season of [[spring (season)|spring]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mythindex.com/roman-mythology/F/Flora.html|title=Flora|publisher=Myth Index |accessdate=}}</ref> – a symbol for nature and flowers (especially the may-flower). While she was otherwise a relatively minor figure in Roman mythology, being one among several [[fertility goddess]]es, her association with the spring gave her particular importance at the coming of springtime,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theoi.com/Nymphe/NympheKhloris.html|title= Khloris, goddess of flowers.|publisher=Theoi Project|accessdate=}}</ref> as did her role as goddess of youth.<ref>H. Nettleship ed., ''A Dictionary of Classical Antiquities'' (1891) p. 238</ref> Her [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] counterpart is [[Chloris]].
== Etymology == Her name is derived from the [[Latin]] word "flos" which means "flower". In modern English, "Flora" also means the plants of a particular region or period.<ref>[http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/flora Dictionary.reference.com]</ref>
==Festival== Her festival, the ''[[Floralia]]'', was held between April 28 and May 3 and symbolized the renewal of the cycle of life, drinking, and flowers.<ref name="NewLarousse">{{Cite book| last1 = Guirand | first1 = Felix | last2 = Aldington | first2 = Richard | last3 = Ames | first3 = Delano | last4 = Graves | first4 = Robert | title = New Larousse Encyclopedia of Mythology | date = December 16, 1987 | publisher = Crescent Books | isbn = 0517004046 | page=201}}</ref> The festival was first instituted in 240 B.C.E, and on the advice of the [[Sibylline books]], she was also given [[Temple of Flora|a temple]] in 238 B.C.E. At the festival, with the men decked in flowers, and the women wearing normally forbidden gay costumes, five days of farces and mimes were enacted&nbsp;– [[ithyphallic]],<ref>P/ Green ed., ''Juvenal: The Sixteen Satires'' (1982) p. 156</ref> and including nudity when called for<ref>H. J. Rose, ''A Handbook of Latin Literature'' (1967) p. 151</ref> – followed by a sixth day of the hunting of goats and hares.<ref>H. Nettleship ed., ''A Dictionary of Classical Antiquities'' (1891) p. 238</ref> On May 23 another (rose) festival was held in her honor.<ref name="NewLarousse" />
Flora's [[Greek mythology|Greek]] equivalent is [[Chloris]], who was a nymph. Flora is married to [[Anemoi|Favonius]], the wind god also known as Zephyr, and her companion was [[Hercules]].
Flora achieved more prominence in the neo-pagan revival of Antiquity among [[Renaissance]] [[humanism|humanists]] than she had ever enjoyed in ancient Rome.{{citeneeded|date=April 2015}}
==Music== Flora is the main character of the ballet ''[[The Awakening of Flora]]''. She is also mentioned in [[Henry Purcell]]'s [[Nymphs and Shepherds]].
==Sculpture== There are many monuments of Flora, e.g. in [[Capitoline Museums]] in [[Rome]] (Italy), in [[Valencia]] (Spain) and [[Szczecin]] (Poland) (see [[Statue of Flora in Szczecin]]).
