{{Refimprove|date=September 2015|talk=No reliable sources - copy to Wiktionary}}
'''Indult Catholic''' was a [[traditionalist Catholic]] [[loaded term]] used from the early 21st century until 2007 as a [[pejorative]] label applied to conservative Catholics who attended only the licit celebrations of the [[Tridentine Mass]] in Latin according to the 1962 edition of the [[Roman Missal]] and regulated by the local bishop through an [[indult]] that conformed to the 1984 [[Congregation for Divine Worship and the Discipline of the Sacraments]] norms in the [[ecclesiastical letter]] ''[[Quattuor abhinc annos]]''.

==Description==
The Tridentine Mass was the normative usage of the [[Roman Rite]] Mass from the time of the [[Council of Trent]] until the liturgical reforms of the [[Second Vatican Council]].

When the [[Mass of Paul VI]], the newer usage of the Roman rite of Mass, replaced the Tridentine Mass, the older usage of the Roman rite of Mass, {{Circa|1970}}, but prior to ''{{lang|la|Quattuor abhinc annos}}'', [[celebret]]s were issued by the [[Holy See]] to some priests permitting them to licitly celebrate the older usage, but bishops complained about this approach.<ref name="Dinges1995"/>{{rp|page=247}}
In 1971 [[Pope Paul VI]] permitted, in what is known as the [[John Heenan (cardinal)|Heenan]] or the [[Agatha Christie indult]], local bishops in the [[Catholic Bishops' Conference of England and Wales]] to permit the occasional celebration of the older usage according to the 1967 modifications to the 1965 edition of the Roman Missal.<ref>{{cite web|author=Sacred Congregation for Divine Worship|date=1971-11-05|title=The "Heenan" indult|website=lms.org.uk|location=Vatican City|publisher=Latin Mass Society|publication-place=London|id=Prot. N. 1897/71|url=http://www.lms.org.uk/resources/documents/heenan-indult|access-date=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111061031/http://www.lms.org.uk/resources/documents/heenan-indult|archivedate=2011-01-11|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref>

In 1984, the Congregation for Divine Worship and the Discipline of the Sacraments issued an indult to diocesan bishops, in ''{{lang|la|Quattuor abhinc annos}}'', which permitted the diocesan bishops to grant indults, under certain conditions, to churches and oratories permitting celebration of the older usage in Latin according to the 1962 edition.<ref name="QuattuorAbhincAnnos1984">{{cite web|author=Congregation for Divine Worship and Discipline of the Sacraments|date=1984-10-03|title=Quattuor abhinc annos|website=adoremus.org|location=St Louis|publisher=Adoremus|url=http://www.adoremus.org/Quattuorabhincannos.html|access-date=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040825175334/http://www.adoremus.org/Quattuorabhincannos.html|archivedate=2004-08-25|deadurl=no}} Translation from ''L'Osservatore Romano'' (English ed.). 1984-10-22.</ref>

Some Traditionalist Catholics practise their faith outside the discipline of the Catholic Church and reject the doctrinal and liturgical reforms of [[Second Vatican Council]].<ref name="Dinges1995">{{cite book|last=Dinges|first=William D.|year=1995|chapter={{ '}}We are what you were': Roman Catholic Traditionalism in America|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=W1KFNeoVo-UC&pg=PA241|editor1-last=Weaver|editor1-first=Mary J.|editor2-last=Appleby|editor2-first=R. Scott|title=Being right: conservative Catholics in America|location=Bloomington [u.a.]|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=9780253329226}}</ref>{{rp|page=242}}{{efn|There is a distinction between conservative Catholics and traditionalist Catholics, the later, which are seen as "the most radicalized segment on the Catholic right and the most representative Catholic analogue to [[Christian fundamentalism|Protestant fundamentalism]]," have organized "counterchurch institutions" and are associated with "antidemocratic political ideologies."<ref name="Dinges1995"/>{{rp|page=242, 244–245}}}}
They claimed that no authorization was required for celebrating the older usage of the Roman rite of Mass. They decried those who accepted the conditions attached to the ''{{lang|la|Quattuor abhinc annos}}'' indult, applying to them the term ''indult Catholics'', and frequently did not recognise them as fellow traditionalists.

In 1988 following the [[Ecône consecrations|canonically illicit consecration, at Ecône]], Switzerland, of four [[Society of St. Pius X]] members as bishops by Archbishop [[Marcel Lefebvre]], John Paul II recommended, in ''[[Ecclesia Dei]]'', a "wide and generous application" of the norms in ''{{lang|la|Quattuor abhinc annos}}'' and established the [[Pontifical Commission Ecclesia Dei|Pontifical Commission ''Ecclesia Dei'']] to facilitate the return of traditionalist Catholics into full communion with the Holy See.

The term ''indult Catholic'' became useless as a [[polemic]] in 2007 when [[Pope Benedict XVI]] promulgated, in ''[[Summorum Pontificum]]'', a universal law for the Catholic Church which reformed the norms about the older usage of the Roman rite of Mass.{{efn|name=PCED2011instruction|The Pontifical Commission ''Ecclesia Dei'' issued an instruction in 2011 that elaborated on the way ''Summorum Pontificum'' must be fulfilled.<ref name="PCED2011">{{cite web|author=Pontifical Commission ''Ecclesia Dei''|date=2011-04-30|title=Instruction on the application of the apostolic letter ''Summorum Pontificum'' of His Holiness Benedict XVI given ''motu proprio''|website=vatican.va|location=|publisher=|url=http://www.vatican.va/roman_curia/pontifical_commissions/ecclsdei/documents/rc_com_ecclsdei_doc_20110430_istr-universae-ecclesiae_en.html|access-date=}}</ref>}} It replaced the norms in ''{{lang|la|Quattuor abhinc annos}}'' and ''{{lang|la|Ecclesia Dei}}'', which regulated through diocesan level indults, with universal church law.{{efn|name=PCED2011instruction}} Benedict XVI wrote that "precise juridical norms" regulating the use of the 1962 Missal were missing because some bishops "feared that the authority of the Council would be called into question."<ref name="SummorumPontificum2007"/> Benedict XVI wrote that while "fidelity to the old Missal became an external mark of identity" in the [[Society of St. Pius X]], "the reasons for the break which arose over this, however, were at a deeper level."<ref name="SummorumPontificum2007">{{cite web|author=Pope Benedict XVI|date=2007-07-07|title=Summorum Pontificum|website=vatican.va|location=|publisher=|url=http://w2.vatican.va/content/benedict-xvi/en/motu_proprio/documents/hf_ben-xvi_motu-proprio_20070707_summorum-pontificum.html}}</ref>

